# Snap Text Extractor

Select an area of the screen to instantly extract and copy text to the clipboard using native Optical Character Recognition (OCR).

## Features
* **Instant Text Extraction:** Select any part of your screen, and the text within that area is instantly processed and copied to your clipboard.
* **Extraction History:** Easily access a history of your up to 15 most recent text extractions right from the GNOME Shell top panel menu.
* **Customizable Shortcut:** Set your own keyboard shortcut for lightning-fast access (default is Super + Shift + T).
* **Visual Notifications:** Get instant system banner notifications when text is successfully extracted or when you copy a previously extracted item from your history.
* **Seamless GNOME Integration:** Built exclusively for GNOME Shell (supports versions 45 through 50) using modern standard APIs.

## System Dependencies
This extension relies on standard, secure, native system tools to capture the screen and perform the OCR extraction. Before using the extension, ensure you have the following packages installed on your system:

**Ubuntu / Debian / Pop!_OS**
Open your terminal and run:
> sudo apt update && sudo apt install tesseract-ocr gnome-screenshot

**Fedora**
Open your terminal and run:
> sudo dnf install tesseract gnome-screenshot

**Arch Linux / Manjaro**
Open your terminal and run:
> sudo pacman -S tesseract tesseract-data-eng gnome-screenshot

## Installation

**Method 1: Local Build**
1. Clone the repository or download the source files.
2. Run the provided build script in your terminal:
> ./build.sh
3. Restart your GNOME Shell:
   * **Wayland:** Log out and log back in.
   * **X11:** Press Alt+F2, type r, and press Enter.
4. Enable the extension via the GNOME Extensions app or by running this command:
> gnome-extensions enable snaptext@cwittenberg

## Usage
1. Press your configured keyboard shortcut (or click the top panel icon and select with a left-click).
2. Click and drag your mouse cursor over the text you wish to extract from your screen.
3. The extracted text is automatically sent to your clipboard, ready to be pasted anywhere.
4. Right-click the panel icon to view your recent history and settings.

